3226   /**
3227    * Returns a new promise that is fulfilled when all of the input promises
3228    * are resolved. If any promise in the list fails, then the returned promise
3229    * will fail with the last error. If they all succeed, then the returned
3230    * promise will succeed, with the results being the results of all the input
3231    * promises. For example: <pre>
3232    *   var p1 = ML.Promise.as(1);
3233    *   var p2 = ML.Promise.as(2);
3234    *   var p3 = ML.Promise.as(3);
3235    *
3236    *   ML.Promise.when(p1, p2, p3).then(function(r1, r2, r3) {
3237    *     console.log(r1);  // prints 1
3238    *     console.log(r2);  // prints 2
3239    *     console.log(r3);  // prints 3
3240    *   });</pre>
3241    *
3242    * The input promises can also be specified as an array: <pre>
3243    *   var promises = [p1, p2, p3];
3244    *   ML.Promise.when(promises).then(function(r1, r2, r3) {
3245    *     console.log(r1);  // prints 1
3246    *     console.log(r2);  // prints 2
3247    *     console.log(r3);  // prints 3
3248    *   });
3249    * </pre>
3250    * @param {Array} promises a list of promises to wait for.
3251    * @return {ML.Promise} the new promise.
3252    */
3253   when: function(promises) {
3254     // Allow passing in Promises as separate arguments instead of an Array.
3255     var objects;
3256     if (promises && _isNullOrUndefined(promises.length)) {
3257       objects = arguments;
3258     } else {
3259       objects = promises;
3260     }
3261     var isAll = _.last(arguments);
3262     isAll = _.isBoolean(isAll) ? isAll : false;
3263 
3264     var total = objects.length;
3265     var hadError = false;
3266     var results = [];
3267     var errors = [];
3268     results.length = objects.length;
3269     errors.length = objects.length;
3270 
3271     if (total === 0) {
3272       if(isAll) {
3273         return Promise.as.call(this, results);
3274       } else {
3275         return Promise.as.apply(this, results);
3276       }
3277     }
3278 
3279     var promise = new Promise();
3280 
3281     var resolveOne = function(i) {
3282       total = total - 1;
3283       if(hadError && !promise._rejected && isAll) {
3284         promise.reject.call(promise, errors[i]);
3285         return;
3286       }
3287 
3288       if (total === 0) {
3289         if (hadError && !promise._rejected) {
3290           promise.reject.call(promise, errors);
3291         } else {
3292           if(isAll) {
3293             if(!promise._rejected) {
3294               promise.resolve.call(promise, results);
3295             } else {
3296               //It's rejected already, so we ignore it.
3297             }
3298           } else {
3299             promise.resolve.apply(promise, results);
3300           }
3301         }
3302       }
3303     };
3304 
3305     _.each(objects, function(object, i) {
3306       if (Promise.is(object)) {
3307         object.then(function(result) {
3308           results[i] = result;
3309           resolveOne(i);
3310         }, function(error) {
3311           errors[i] = error;
3312           hadError = true;
3313           resolveOne(i);
3314         });
3315       } else {
3316         results[i] = object;
3317         resolveOne(i);
3318       }
3319     });
3320 
3321     return promise;
3322   },

3347   race: function(promises) {

3425 _.extend(Promise.prototype, /** @lends ML.Promise.prototype */ {

3427   /**
3428    * Marks this promise as fulfilled, firing any callbacks waiting on it.
3429    * @param {Object} result the result to pass to the callbacks.
3430    */
3431   resolve: function(result) {
3432     if (this._resolved || this._rejected) {
3433       throw "A promise was resolved even though it had already been " +
3434         (this._resolved ? "resolved" : "rejected") + ".";
3435     }
3436     this._resolved = true;
3437     this._result = arguments;
3438     var results = arguments;
3439     _.each(this._resolvedCallbacks, function(resolvedCallback) {
3440       resolvedCallback.apply(this, results);
3441     });
3442     this._resolvedCallbacks = [];
3443     this._rejectedCallbacks = [];
3444   },
3445 
3446   doResolve: function(fn){
3447     if (!fn) return;
3448     var done = false;
3449     var self = this;
3450     try {
3451       fn(function (value) {
3452         if (done) return;
3453         done = true;
3454         self.resolve.call(self, value);
3455       }, function (reason) {
3456            if (done) return;
3457            done = true;
3458            self.reject.call(self, reason);
3459       });
3460     } catch (ex) {
3461       if (done) return;
3462       done = true;
3463       self.reject.call(self, ex);
3464     }
3465   },
3466 
3467   /**
3468    * Marks this promise as fulfilled, firing any callbacks waiting on it.
3469    * @param {Object} error the error to pass to the callbacks.
3470    */
3471   reject: function(error) {

3473       throw "A promise was rejected even though it had already been " +
3474         (this._resolved ? "resolved" : "rejected") + ".";
3475     }
3476     this._rejected = true;
3477     this._error = error;
3478     _.each(this._rejectedCallbacks, function(rejectedCallback) {
3479       rejectedCallback(error);
3480     });
3481     this._resolvedCallbacks = [];
3482     this._rejectedCallbacks = [];
3483   },

3485   /**
3486    * Adds callbacks to be called when this promise is fulfilled. Returns a new
3487    * Promise that will be fulfilled when the callback is complete. It allows
3488    * chaining. If the callback itself returns a Promise, then the one returned
3489    * by "then" will not be fulfilled until that one returned by the callback
3490    * is fulfilled.
3491    * @param {Function} resolvedCallback Function that is called when this
3492    * Promise is resolved. Once the callback is complete, then the Promise
3493    * returned by "then" will also be fulfilled.
3494    * @param {Function} rejectedCallback Function that is called when this
3495    * Promise is rejected with an error. Once the callback is complete, then
3496    * the promise returned by "then" with be resolved successfully. If
3497    * rejectedCallback is null, or it returns a rejected Promise, then the
3498    * Promise returned by "then" will be rejected with that error.
3499    * @return {ML.Promise} A new Promise that will be fulfilled after this
3500    * Promise is fulfilled and either callback has completed. If the callback
3501    * returned a Promise, then this Promise will not be fulfilled until that
3502    * one is.
3503    */
3504   then: function(resolvedCallback, rejectedCallback) {
3505     var promise = new Promise();
3506 
3507     var wrappedResolvedCallback = function() {
3508       var result = arguments;
3509       if (resolvedCallback) {
3510         if (Promise._isPromisesAPlusCompliant) {
3511           try {
3512             result = [resolvedCallback.apply(this, result)];
3513           } catch (e) {
3514             if(Promise._debugError && e) {
3515               console.error('Error occurred in promise resolve callback.', e.stack || e);
3516             }
3517             result = [Promise.error(e)];
3518           }
3519         } else {
3520           result = [resolvedCallback.apply(this, result)];
3521         }
3522       }
3523       if (result.length === 1 && Promise.is(result[0])) {
3524         result[0].then(function() {
3525           promise.resolve.apply(promise, arguments);
3526         }, function(error) {
3527           promise.reject(error);
3528         });
3529       } else {
3530         promise.resolve.apply(promise, result);
3531       }
3532     };
3533 
3534     var wrappedRejectedCallback = function(error) {
3535       var result = [];
3536       if (rejectedCallback) {
3537         if (Promise._isPromisesAPlusCompliant) {
3538           try {
3539             result = [rejectedCallback(error)];
3540           } catch (e) {
3541             if(Promise._debugError && e) {
3542               console.error('Error occurred in promise reject callback.', e.stack || e);
3543             }
3544             result = [Promise.error(e)];
3545           }
3546         } else {
3547           result = [rejectedCallback(error)];
3548         }
3549         if (result.length === 1 && Promise.is(result[0])) {
3550           result[0].then(function() {
3551             promise.resolve.apply(promise, arguments);
3552           }, function(error) {
3553             promise.reject(error);
3554           });
3555         } else {
3556           if (Promise._isPromisesAPlusCompliant) {
3557             promise.resolve.apply(promise, result);
3558           } else {
3559             promise.reject(result[0]);
3560           }
3561         }
3562       } else {
3563         promise.reject(error);
3564       }
3565     };
3566 
3567     var runLater = function(func) {
3568       func.call();
3569     };
3570     if (Promise._isPromisesAPlusCompliant) {
3571       if (typeof(window) !== 'undefined' && _.isFunction(window.setImmediate)) {
3572         runLater = function(func) {
3573           window.setImmediate(func);
3574         };
3575       } else if (typeof(process) !== 'undefined' && process.nextTick) {
3576         runLater = function(func) {
3577            process.nextTick(func);
3578         };
3579       } else if (typeof(setTimeout) !== 'undefined' && _.isFunction(setTimeout)) {
3580         runLater = function(func) {
3581           setTimeout(func, 0);
3582         };
3583       }
3584     }
3585 
3586     var self = this;
3587     if (this._resolved) {
3588       runLater(function() {
3589         wrappedResolvedCallback.apply(self, self._result);
3590       });
3591     } else if (this._rejected) {
3592       runLater(function() {
3593         wrappedRejectedCallback.apply(self, [self._error]);
3594       });
3595     } else {
3596       this._resolvedCallbacks.push(wrappedResolvedCallback);
3597       this._rejectedCallbacks.push(wrappedRejectedCallback);
3598     }
3599 
3600     return promise;
3601   },
3602 
3603   /**
3604    * Add handlers to be called when the Promise object is rejected.
3605    *
3606    * @param {Function} rejectedCallback Function that is called when this
3607    *                   Promise is rejected with an error.
3608    * @return {ML.Promise} A new Promise that will be fulfilled after this
3609    *                   Promise is fulfilled and either callback has completed. If the callback
3610    * returned a Promise, then this Promise will not be fulfilled until that
3611    *                   one is.
3612    * @function
3613    */
3614   catch: function(onRejected) {
3615     return this.then(undefined, onRejected);
3616   },
3617 
3618   /**
3619    * Add handlers to be called when the promise
3620    * is either resolved or rejected
3621    */
3622   always: function(callback) {
3623     return this.then(callback, callback);
3624   },
3625 
3626   /**
3627    * Add handlers to be called when the Promise object is resolved
3628    */
3629   done: function(callback) {
3630     return this.then(callback);
3631   },
3632 
3633   /**
3634    * Add handlers to be called when the Promise object is rejected
3635    */
3636   fail: function(callback) {
3637     return this.then(null, callback);
3638   },
3639 
3640   /**
3641    * Run the given callbacks after this promise is fulfilled.
3642    * @param optionsOrCallback {} A Backbone-style options callback, or a
3643    * callback function. If this is an options object and contains a "model"
3644    * attributes, that will be passed to error callbacks as the first argument.
3645    * @param model {} If truthy, this will be passed as the first result of
3646    * error callbacks. This is for Backbone-compatability.
3647    * @return {ML.Promise} A promise that will be resolved after the
3648    * callbacks are run, with the same result as this.
3649    */
3650   _thenRunCallbacks: function(optionsOrCallback, model) {
3651     var options;
3652     if (_.isFunction(optionsOrCallback)) {
3653       var callback = optionsOrCallback;
3654       options = {
3655         success: function(result) {
3656           callback(result, null);
3657         },
3658         error: function(error) {
3659           callback(null, error);
3660         }
3661       };
3662     } else {
3663       options = _.clone(optionsOrCallback);
3664     }
3665     options = options || {};
3666 
3667     return this.then(function(result) {
3668       if (options.success) {
3669         options.success.apply(this, arguments);
3670       } else if (model) {
3671         // When there's no callback, a sync event should be triggered.
3672         model.trigger('sync', model, result, options);
3673       }
3674       return Promise.as.apply(Promise, arguments);
3675     }, function(error) {
3676       if (options.error) {
3677         if (!_.isUndefined(model)) {
3678           options.error(model, error);
3679         } else {
3680           options.error(error);
3681         }
3682       } else if (model) {
3683         // When there's no error callback, an error event should be triggered.
3684         model.trigger('error', model, error, options);
3685       }
3686       // By explicitly returning a rejected Promise, this will work with
3687       // either jQuery or Promises/A semantics.
3688       return Promise.error(error);
3689     });
3690   },
3691 
3692   /**
3693    * Adds a callback function that should be called regardless of whether
3694    * this promise failed or succeeded. The callback will be given either the
3695    * array of results for its first argument, or the error as its second,
3696    * depending on whether this Promise was rejected or resolved. Returns a
3697    * new Promise, like "then" would.
3698    * @param {Function} continuation the callback.
3699    */
3700   _continueWith: function(continuation) {
3701     return this.then(function() {
3702       return continuation(arguments, null);
3703     }, function(error) {
3704       return continuation(null, error);
3705     });
3706   }
3707 
3708 });

3711  * Alias of ML.Promise.prototype.always
3712  * @function
3713  * @see ML.Promise#always
3714  */
3715 Promise.prototype.finally = Promise.prototype.always;

3718  * Alias of ML.Promise.prototype.done
3719  * @function

3722 Promise.prototype.try = Promise.prototype.done;

3730 // ML.Query is a way to create a list of ML.Objects.
3731 module.exports = function(ML) {
3732   /**
3733    * Creates a new maxleap ML.Query for the given ML.Object subclass.
3734    * @param objectClass -
3735    *   An instance of a subclass of ML.Object, or a ML className string.
3736    * @class
3737    *
3738    * <p>ML.Query defines a query that is used to fetch ML.Objects. The
3739    * most common use case is finding all objects that match a query through the
3740    * <code>find</code> method. For example, this sample code fetches all objects
3741    * of class <code>MyClass</code>. It calls a different function depending on
3742    * whether the fetch succeeded or not.
3743    *
3744    * <pre>
3745    * var query = new ML.Query(MyClass);
3746    * query.find({
3747    *   success: function(results) {
3748    *     // results is an array of ML.Object.
3749    *   },
3750    *
3751    *   error: function(error) {
3752    *     // error is an instance of ML.Error.
3753    *   }
3754    * });</pre></p>
3755    *
3756    * <p>A ML.Query can also be used to retrieve a single object whose id is
3757    * known, through the get method. For example, this sample code fetches an
3758    * object of class <code>MyClass</code> and id <code>myId</code>. It calls a
3759    * different function depending on whether the fetch succeeded or not.
3760    *
3761    * <pre>
3762    * var query = new ML.Query(MyClass);
3763    * query.get(myId, {
3764    *   success: function(object) {
3765    *     // object is an instance of ML.Object.
3766    *   },
3767    *
3768    *   error: function(object, error) {
3769    *     // error is an instance of ML.Error.
3770    *   }
3771    * });</pre></p>
3772    *
3773    * <p>A ML.Query can also be used to count the number of objects that match
3774    * the query without retrieving all of those objects. For example, this
3775    * sample code counts the number of objects of the class <code>MyClass</code>
3776    * <pre>
3777    * var query = new ML.Query(MyClass);
3778    * query.count({
3779    *   success: function(number) {
3780    *     // There are number instances of MyClass.
3781    *   },
3782    *
3783    *   error: function(error) {
3784    *     // error is an instance of ML.Error.
3785    *   }
3786    * });</pre></p>
3787    */
3788   ML.Query = function(objectClass) {
3789     if (_.isString(objectClass)) {
3790       objectClass = ML.Object._getSubclass(objectClass);
3791     }
3792 
3793     this.objectClass = objectClass;
3794 
3795     this.className = objectClass.prototype.className;
3796 
3797     this._where = {};
3798     this._include = [];
3799     this._limit = -1; // negative limit means, do not send a limit
3800     this._skip = 0;
3801     this._extraOptions = {};
3802   };
3803 
3804   /**
3805    * Constructs a ML.Query that is the OR of the passed in queries.  For
3806    * example:
3807    * <pre>var compoundQuery = ML.Query.or(query1, query2, query3);</pre>
3808    *
3809    * will create a compoundQuery that is an or of the query1, query2, and
3810    * query3.
3811    * @param {...ML.Query} var_args The list of queries to OR.
3812    * @return {ML.Query} The query that is the OR of the passed in queries.
3813    */
3814   ML.Query.or = function() {
3815     var queries = _.toArray(arguments);
3816     var className = null;
3817     ML._arrayEach(queries, function(q) {
3818       if (_.isNull(className)) {
3819         className = q.className;
3820       }
3821 
3822       if (className !== q.className) {
3823         throw "All queries must be for the same class";
3824       }
3825     });
3826     var query = new ML.Query(className);
3827     query._orQuery(queries);
3828     return query;
3829   };
3830 
3831   /**
3832    * Constructs a ML.Query that is the AND of the passed in queries.  For
3833    * example:
3834    * <pre>var compoundQuery = ML.Query.and(query1, query2, query3);</pre>
3835    *
3836    * will create a compoundQuery that is an 'and' of the query1, query2, and
3837    * query3.
3838    * @param {...ML.Query} var_args The list of queries to AND.
3839    * @return {ML.Query} The query that is the AND of the passed in queries.
3840    */
3841   ML.Query.and = function() {
3842     var queries = _.toArray(arguments);
3843     var className = null;
3844     ML._arrayEach(queries, function(q) {
3845       if (_.isNull(className)) {
3846         className = q.className;
3847       }
3848 
3849       if (className !== q.className) {
3850         throw "All queries must be for the same class";
3851       }
3852     });
3853     var query = new ML.Query(className);
3854     query._andQuery(queries);
3855     return query;
3856   };

3870   ML.Query.doCloudQuery = function(cql, pvalues, options) {

3879     return request.then(function(response) {

4262       // modifiers

4264       if (regex.multiline) { modifiers += 'm'; }

4267         this._addCondition(key, "$options", modifiers);

4432    addAscending: function(key){
4433      if(this._order)

4473     near: function(key, point) {

4524     /**

4530      *     The lower-left inclusive corner of the box.

4532      *     The upper-right inclusive corner of the box.
4533      * @return {ML.Query} Returns the query, so you can chain this call.
4534      */
4535     withinGeoBox: function(key, southwest, northeast) {
4536       if (!(southwest instanceof ML.GeoPoint)) {
4537         southwest = new ML.GeoPoint(southwest);
4538       }
4539       if (!(northeast instanceof ML.GeoPoint)) {
4540         northeast = new ML.GeoPoint(northeast);
4541       }
4542       this._addCondition(key, '$within', { '$box': [southwest, northeast] });
4543       return this;

4546     /**
4547      * Include nested ML.Objects for the provided key.  You can use dot
4548      * notation to specify which fields in the included object are also fetch.
4549      * @param {String} key The name of the key to include.
4550      * @return {ML.Query} Returns the query, so you can chain this call.
4551      */
4552     include: function() {
4553       var self = this;
4554       ML._arrayEach(arguments, function(key) {
4555         if (_.isArray(key)) {
4556           self._include = self._include.concat(key);
4557         } else {
4558           self._include.push(key);
4559         }
4560       });
4561       return this;
4562     },
4563 
4564     /**
4565      * Restrict the fields of the returned ML.Objects to include only the
4566      * provided keys.  If this is called multiple times, then all of the keys
4567      * specified in each of the calls will be included.
4568      * @param {Array} keys The names of the keys to include.
4569      * @return {ML.Query} Returns the query, so you can chain this call.
4570      */
4571     select: function() {
4572       var self = this;
4573       this._select = this._select || [];
4574       ML._arrayEach(arguments, function(key) {
4575         if (_.isArray(key)) {
4576           self._select = self._select.concat(key);
4577         } else {
4578           self._select.push(key);
4579         }
4580       });
4581       return this;
4582     },
4583 
4584     /**
4585      * Iterates over each result of a query, calling a callback for each one. If
4586      * the callback returns a promise, the iteration will not continue until
4587      * that promise has been fulfilled. If the callback returns a rejected
4588      * promise, then iteration will stop with that error. The items are
4589      * processed in an unspecified order. The query may not have any sort order,
4590      * and may not use limit or skip.
4591      * @param callback {Function} Callback that will be called with each result
4592      *     of the query.
4593      * @param options {Object} An optional Backbone-like options object with
4594      *     success and error callbacks that will be invoked once the iteration
4595      *     has finished.
4596      * @return {ML.Promise} A promise that will be fulfilled once the
4597      *     iteration has completed.
4598      */
4599     each: function(callback, options) {
4600       options = options || {};
4601 
4602       if (this._order || this._skip || (this._limit >= 0)) {
4603         var error =
4604           "Cannot iterate on a query with sort, skip, or limit.";
4605         return ML.Promise.error(error)._thenRunCallbacks(options);
4606       }
4607 
4608       var promise = new ML.Promise();
4609 
4610       var query = new ML.Query(this.objectClass);
4611       // We can override the batch size from the options.
4612       // This is undocumented, but useful for testing.
4613       query._limit = options.batchSize || 100;
4614       query._where = _.clone(this._where);
4615       query._include = _.clone(this._include);
4616 
4617       query.ascending('objectId');
4618 
4619       var finished = false;
4620       return ML.Promise._continueWhile(function() {
4621         return !finished;
4622 
4623       }, function() {
4624         return query.find().then(function(results) {
4625           var callbacksDone = ML.Promise.as();
4626           ML._.each(results, function(result) {
4627             callbacksDone = callbacksDone.then(function() {
4628               return callback(result);
4629             });
4630           });
4631 
4632           return callbacksDone.then(function() {
4633             if (results.length >= query._limit) {
4634               query.greaterThan("objectId", results[results.length - 1].id);
4635             } else {
4636               finished = true;
4637             }
4638           });
4639         });
4640       })._thenRunCallbacks(options);
4641     }
4642   };
4643 
4644    ML.FriendShipQuery = ML.Query._extend({
4645      _objectClass: ML.User,
4646      _newObject: function(){
4647       return new ML.User();
4648     },
4649      _processResult: function(json){
4650       var user = json[this._friendshipTag];
4651       if(user.__type === 'Pointer' && user.className === '_User'){
4652         delete user.__type;
4653         delete user.className;
4654       }
4655       return user;
4656     },
4657    });

4664 module.exports = function(ML) {
4665   /**
4666    * Creates a new Relation for the given parent object and key. This
4667    * constructor should rarely be used directly, but rather created by
4668    * ML.Object.relation.
4669    * @param {ML.Object} parent The parent of this relation.
4670    * @param {String} key The key for this relation on the parent.
4671    * @see ML.Object#relation
4672    * @class
4673    *
4674    * <p>
4675    * A class that is used to access all of the children of a many-to-many
4676    * relationship.  Each instance of ML.Relation is associated with a
4677    * particular parent object and key.
4678    * </p>
4679    */
4680   ML.Relation = function(parent, key) {
4681     if (! _.isString(key)) {
4682       throw new TypeError('key must be a string');
4683     }
4684     this.parent = parent;
4685     this.key = key;
4686     this.targetClassName = null;
4687   };
4688 
4689   /**
4690    * Creates a query that can be used to query the parent objects in this relation.
4691    * @param {String} parentClass The parent class or name.
4692    * @param {String} relationKey The relation field key in parent.
4693    * @param {ML.Object} child The child object.
4694    * @return {ML.Query}
4695    */
4696   ML.Relation.reverseQuery = function(parentClass, relationKey, child){
4697     var query = new ML.Query(parentClass);
4698     query.equalTo(relationKey, child._toPointer());
4699     return query;
4700   };
4701 
4702   ML.Relation.prototype = {
4703     /**
4704      * Makes sure that this relation has the right parent and key.
4705      */
4706     _ensureParentAndKey: function(parent, key) {
4707       this.parent = this.parent || parent;
4708       this.key = this.key || key;
4709       if (this.parent !== parent) {
4710         throw "Internal Error. Relation retrieved from two different Objects.";
4711       }
4712       if (this.key !== key) {
4713         throw "Internal Error. Relation retrieved from two different keys.";
4714       }
4715     },
4716 
4717     /**
4718      * Adds a ML.Object or an array of ML.Objects to the relation.
4719      * @param {} objects The item or items to add.
4720      */
4721     add: function(objects) {
4722       if (!_.isArray(objects)) {
4723         objects = [objects];
4724       }
4725 
4726       var change = new ML.Op.Relation(objects, []);
4727       this.parent.set(this.key, change);
4728       this.targetClassName = change._targetClassName;
4729     },
4730 
4731     /**
4732      * Removes a ML.Object or an array of ML.Objects from this relation.
4733      * @param {} objects The item or items to remove.
4734      */
4735     remove: function(objects) {
4736       if (!_.isArray(objects)) {
4737         objects = [objects];
4738       }
4739 
4740       var change = new ML.Op.Relation([], objects);
4741       this.parent.set(this.key, change);
4742       this.targetClassName = change._targetClassName;
4743     },
4744 
4745     /**
4746      * Returns a JSON version of the object suitable for saving to disk.
4747      * @return {Object}
4748      */
4749     toJSON: function() {
4750       return { "__type": "Relation", "className": this.targetClassName };
4751     },
4752 
4753     /**
4754      * Returns a ML.Query that is limited to objects in this
4755      * relation.
4756      * @return {ML.Query}
4757      */
4758     query: function() {
4759       var targetClass;
4760       var query;
4761       if (!this.targetClassName) {
4762         targetClass = ML.Object._getSubclass(this.parent.className);
4763         query = new ML.Query(targetClass);
4764         query._extraOptions.redirectClassNameForKey = this.key;
4765       } else {
4766         targetClass = ML.Object._getSubclass(this.targetClassName);
4767         query = new ML.Query(targetClass);
4768       }
4769       query._addCondition("$relatedTo", "object", this.parent._toPointer());
4770       query._addCondition("$relatedTo", "key", this.key);
4771 
4772       return query;
4773     }
4774   };
4775 };

4873       if (_.isString(provider)) {
4874         authType = provider;
4875         provider = ML.User._authProviders[authType];
4876       } else {
4877         authType = provider.getAuthType();
4878       }
4879       var authData = this.get('authData');
4880       if (!authData || !provider) {
4881         return;
4882       }
4883       var success = provider.restoreAuthentication(authData[authType]);
4884       if (!success) {
4885         this._unlinkFrom(provider);
4886       }
4887     },
4888 
4889     _handleSaveResult: function(makeCurrent) {
4890       // Clean up and synchronize the authData object, removing any unset values
4891       if (makeCurrent) {
4892         this._isCurrentUser = true;
4893       }
4894       this._cleanupAuthData();
4895       this._synchronizeAllAuthData();
4896       // Don't keep the password around.
4897       delete this._serverData.password;
4898       this._rebuildEstimatedDataForKey("password");
4899       this._refreshCache();
4900       if (makeCurrent || this.isCurrent()) {
4901         ML.User._saveCurrentUser(this);
4902       }
4903     },
4904 
4905     /**
4906      * Unlike in the Android/iOS SDKs, logInWith is unnecessary, since you can
4907      * call linkWith on the user (even if it doesn't exist yet on the server).
4908      */
4909     _linkWith: function(provider, options) {
4910       var authType;
4911       if (_.isString(provider)) {
4912         authType = provider;
4913         provider = ML.User._authProviders[provider];
4914       } else {
4915         authType = provider.getAuthType();
4916       }
4917       if (_.has(options, 'authData')) {
4918         var authData = this.get('authData') || {};
4919         authData[authType] = options.authData;
4920         this.set('authData', authData);
4921 
4922         // Overridden so that the user can be made the current user.
4923         var newOptions = _.clone(options) || {};
4924         newOptions.success = function(model) {
4925           model._handleSaveResult(true);
4926           if (options.success) {
4927             options.success.apply(this, arguments);
4928           }
4929         };
4930         return this.save({'authData': authData}, newOptions);
4931       } else {
4932         var self = this;
4933         var promise = new ML.Promise();
4934         provider.authenticate({
4935           success: function(provider, result) {
4936             self._linkWith(provider, {
4937               authData: result,
4938               success: options.success,
4939               error: options.error
4940             }).then(function() {
4941               promise.resolve(self);
4942             });
4943           },
4944           error: function(provider, error) {
4945             if (options.error) {
4946               options.error(self, error);
4947             }
4948             promise.reject(error);
4949           }
4950         });
4951         return promise;
4952       }
4953     },
4954 
4955     /**
4956      * Unlinks a user from a service.
4957      */
4958     _unlinkFrom: function(provider, options) {
4959       var authType;
4960       if (_.isString(provider)) {
4961         authType = provider;
4962         provider = ML.User._authProviders[provider];
4963       } else {
4964         authType = provider.getAuthType();
4965       }
4966       var newOptions = _.clone(options);
4967       var self = this;
4968       newOptions.authData = null;
4969       newOptions.success = function(model) {
4970         self._synchronizeAuthData(provider);
4971         if (options.success) {
4972           options.success.apply(this, arguments);
4973         }
4974       };
4975       return this._linkWith(provider, newOptions);
4976     },
4977 
4978     /**
4979      * Checks whether a user is linked to a service.
4980      */
4981     _isLinked: function(provider) {
4982       var authType;
4983       if (_.isString(provider)) {
4984         authType = provider;
4985       } else {
4986         authType = provider.getAuthType();
4987       }
4988       var authData = this.get('authData') || {};
4989       return !!authData[authType];
4990     },
4991 
4992     /**
4993      * Deauthenticates all providers.
4994      */
4995     _logOutWithAll: function() {
4996       var authData = this.get('authData');
4997       if (!authData) {
4998         return;
4999       }
5000       var self = this;
5001       ML._objectEach(this.get('authData'), function(value, key) {
5002         self._logOutWith(key);
5003       });
5004     },
5005 
5006     /**
5007      * Deauthenticates a single provider (e.g. removing access tokens from the
5008      * Facebook SDK).
5009      */
5010     _logOutWith: function(provider) {
5011       if (!this.isCurrent()) {
5012         return;
5013       }
5014       if (_.isString(provider)) {
5015         provider = ML.User._authProviders[provider];
5016       }
5017       if (provider && provider.deauthenticate) {
5018         provider.deauthenticate();
5019       }
5020     },

5022     /**
5023      * Signs up a new user. You should call this instead of save for
5024      * new ML.Users. This will create a new ML.User on the server, and
5025      * also persist the session on disk so that you can access the user using
5026      * <code>current</code>.
5027      *
5028      * <p>A username and password must be set before calling signUp.</p>
5029      *
5030      * <p>Calls options.success or options.error on completion.</p>
5031      *
5032      * @param {Object} attrs Extra fields to set on the new user, or null.
5033      * @param {Object} options A Backbone-style options object.
5034      * @return {ML.Promise} A promise that is fulfilled when the signup
5035      *     finishes.
5036      * @see ML.User.signUp
5037      */
5038     signUp: function(attrs, options) {
5039       var error;
5040       options = options || {};
5041 
5042       var username = (attrs && attrs.username) || this.get("username");
5043       if (!username || (username === "")) {
5044         error = new ML.Error(
5045             ML.Error.OTHER_CAUSE,
5046             "Cannot sign up user with an empty name.");
5047         if (options && options.error) {
5048           options.error(this, error);
5049         }
5050         return ML.Promise.error(error);
5051       }
5052 
5053       var password = (attrs && attrs.password) || this.get("password");
5054       if (!password || (password === "")) {
5055         error = new ML.Error(
5056             ML.Error.OTHER_CAUSE,
5057             "Cannot sign up user with an empty password.");
5058         if (options && options.error) {
5059           options.error(this, error);
5060         }
5061         return ML.Promise.error(error);
5062       }
5063 
5064       // Overridden so that the user can be made the current user.
5065       var newOptions = _.clone(options);
5066       newOptions.success = function(model) {
5067         model._handleSaveResult(true);
5068         if (options.success) {
5069           options.success.apply(this, arguments);
5070         }
5071       };
5072       return this.save(attrs, newOptions);
5073     },
5074 
5075     /**
5076      * Signs up a new anonymous user.
5077      * @return {Promise} A promise that is resolved when the signup
5078      *     finishes.
5079      */
5080     anonymousSignUp: function () {
5081       var model = this;
5082       var authData = {
5083         anonymous: {
5084           id: uuid.v1()
5085         }
5086       };
5087       model.set('authData', authData);
5088       return this.save().then(function (resp) {
5089         model._handleSaveResult();
5090         return model;
5091       });
5092     },
5093 
5094     /**
5095      * Signs up a new user with mobile phone and sms code.
5096      * You should call this instead of save for
5097      * new ML.Users. This will create a new ML.User on the server, and
5098      * also persist the session on disk so that you can access the user using
5099      * <code>current</code>.
5100      *
5101      * <p>A username and password must be set before calling signUp.</p>
5102      *
5103      * <p>Calls options.success or options.error on completion.</p>
5104      *
5105      * @param {Object} attrs Extra fields to set on the new user, or null.
5106      * @param {Object} options A Backbone-style options object.
5107      * @return {ML.Promise} A promise that is fulfilled when the signup
5108      *     finishes.
5109      * @see ML.User.signUpOrlogInWithMobilePhone
5110      * @see ML.Cloud.requestSmsCode
5111      */
5112     signUpOrlogInWithMobilePhone: function(attrs, options) {
5113       var error;
5114       options = options || {};
5115 
5116       var mobilePhoneNumber = (attrs && attrs.mobilePhoneNumber) ||
5117                               this.get("mobilePhoneNumber");
5118       if (!mobilePhoneNumber || (mobilePhoneNumber === "")) {
5119         error = new ML.Error(
5120             ML.Error.OTHER_CAUSE,
5121             "Cannot sign up or login user by mobilePhoneNumber " +
5122             "with an empty mobilePhoneNumber.");
5123         if (options && options.error) {
5124           options.error(this, error);
5125         }
5126         return ML.Promise.error(error);
5127       }
5128 
5129       var smsCode = (attrs && attrs.smsCode) || this.get("smsCode");
5130       if (!smsCode || (smsCode === "")) {
5131         error = new ML.Error(
5132             ML.Error.OTHER_CAUSE,
5133              "Cannot sign up or login user by mobilePhoneNumber  " +
5134              "with an empty smsCode.");
5135         if (options && options.error) {
5136           options.error(this, error);
5137         }
5138         return ML.Promise.error(error);
5139       }
5140 
5141       // Overridden so that the user can be made the current user.
5142       var newOptions = _.clone(options);
5143       newOptions._makeRequest = function(route, className, id, method, json) {
5144         return ML._request('usersByMobilePhone', null, null, "POST", json);
5145       };
5146       newOptions.success = function(model) {
5147         model._handleSaveResult(true);
5148         delete model.attributes.smsCode;
5149         delete model._serverData.smsCode;
5150         if (options.success) {
5151           options.success.apply(this, arguments);
5152         }
5153       };
5154       return this.save(attrs, newOptions);
5155     },

5157     /**
5158      * Logs in a ML.User. On success, this saves the session to localStorage,
5159      * so you can retrieve the currently logged in user using
5160      * <code>current</code>.
5161      *
5162      * <p>A username and password must be set before calling logIn.</p>
5163      *
5164      * <p>Calls options.success or options.error on completion.</p>
5165      *
5166      * @param {Object} options A Backbone-style options object.
5167      * @see ML.User.logIn
5168      * @return {ML.Promise} A promise that is fulfilled with the user when
5169      *     the login is complete.
5170      */
5171     logIn: function(options) {
5172       options = options || {};
5173       var model = this;
5174       var request = ML._request(options.loginUrl || "login", null, null, "POST", this.toJSON());
5175       return request.then(function(resp, status, xhr) {
5176         var serverAttrs = model.parse(resp, status, xhr);
5177         model._finishFetch(serverAttrs);
5178         model._handleSaveResult(true);
5179         if(!serverAttrs.smsCode)
5180           delete model.attributes['smsCode'];
5181         return model;
5182       })._thenRunCallbacks(options, this);
5183     },
5184 
5185     /**
5186      * @see ML.Object#save
5187      */
5188     save: function(arg1, arg2, arg3) {
5189       var i, attrs, current, options, saved;
5190       if (_.isObject(arg1) || _.isNull(arg1) || _.isUndefined(arg1)) {
5191         attrs = arg1;
5192         options = arg2;
5193       } else {
5194         attrs = {};
5195         attrs[arg1] = arg2;
5196         options = arg3;
5197       }
5198       options = options || {};
5199 
5200       var newOptions = _.clone(options);
5201       newOptions.success = function(model) {
5202         model._handleSaveResult(false);
5203         if (options.success) {
5204           options.success.apply(this, arguments);
5205         }
5206       };
5207       return ML.Object.prototype.save.call(this, attrs, newOptions);
5208     },

5215      *     success and error callbacks that will be invoked once the iteration

5224       }

5226       if(!userObjectId){

5228       }

5230       var request = ML._request(route, null, null, 'POST', null);
5231       return request._thenRunCallbacks(options);
5232     },

5534     signUpOrlogInWithMobilePhone: function(mobilePhoneNumber, smsCode, attrs, options) {

5740     /**
5741      * Retrieves the currently logged in MLUser with a valid session,
5742      * either from memory or localStorage, if necessary.
5743      * @return {ML.Object} The currently logged in ML.User.
5744      */
5745     current: function() {
5746       if (ML.User._currentUser) {
5747         return ML.User._currentUser;
5748       }
5749 
5750       if (ML.User._currentUserMatchesDisk) {
5751 
5752         return ML.User._currentUser;
5753       }
5754 
5755       // Load the user from local storage.
5756       ML.User._currentUserMatchesDisk = true;
5757 
5758       var userData = ML.localStorage.getItem(ML._getMLPath(
5759           ML.User._CURRENT_USER_KEY));
5760       if (!userData) {
5761 
5762         return null;
5763       }
5764       ML.User._currentUser = ML.Object._create("_User");
5765       ML.User._currentUser._isCurrentUser = true;
5766 
5767       var json = JSON.parse(userData);
5768       ML.User._currentUser.id = json._id;
5769       delete json._id;
5770       ML.User._currentUser._sessionToken = json._sessionToken;
5771       delete json._sessionToken;
5772       ML.User._currentUser._finishFetch(json);
5773       //ML.User._currentUser.set(json);
5774 
5775       ML.User._currentUser._synchronizeAllAuthData();
5776       ML.User._currentUser._refreshCache();
5777       ML.User._currentUser._opSetQueue = [{}];
5778       return ML.User._currentUser;
5779     },
5780 
5781     /**
5782      * Persists a user as currentUser to localStorage, and into the singleton.
5783      */
5784     _saveCurrentUser: function(user) {
5785       if (ML.User._currentUser !== user) {
5786         ML.User.logOut();
5787       }
5788       user._isCurrentUser = true;
5789       ML.User._currentUser = user;
5790       ML.User._currentUserMatchesDisk = true;
5791 
5792       var json = user.toJSON();
5793       json._id = user.id;
5794       json._sessionToken = user._sessionToken;
5795       ML.localStorage.setItem(
5796           ML._getMLPath(ML.User._CURRENT_USER_KEY),
5797           JSON.stringify(json));
5798     },
5799 
5800     _registerAuthenticationProvider: function(provider) {
5801       ML.User._authProviders[provider.getAuthType()] = provider;
5802       // Synchronize the current user with the auth provider.
5803       if (ML.User.current()) {
5804         ML.User.current()._synchronizeAuthData(provider.getAuthType());
5805       }
5806     },
5807 
5808     _logInWith: function(provider, options) {
5809       var user = ML.Object._create("_User");
5810       return user._linkWith(provider, options);
5811     }

5842   // Shared empty constructor function to aid in prototype-chain creation.
5843   var EmptyConstructor = function () {
5844   };

5846 
5847   // Helper function to correctly set up the prototype chain, for subclasses.
5848   // Similar to `goog.inherits`, but uses a hash of prototype properties and
5849   // class properties to be extended.
5850   var inherits = function (parent, protoProps, staticProps) {
5851     var child;
5852 
5853     // The constructor function for the new subclass is either defined by you
5854     // (the "constructor" property in your `extend` definition), or defaulted
5855     // by us to simply call the parent's constructor.
5856     if (protoProps && protoProps.hasOwnProperty('constructor')) {
5857       child = protoProps.constructor;
5858     } else {
5859       /** @ignore */
5860       child = function () {
5861         parent.apply(this, arguments);
5862       };
5863     }
5864 
5865     // Inherit class (static) properties from parent.
5866     ML._.extend(child, parent);
5867 
5868     // Set the prototype chain to inherit from `parent`, without calling
5869     // `parent`'s constructor function.
5870     EmptyConstructor.prototype = parent.prototype;
5871     child.prototype = new EmptyConstructor();
5872 
5873     // Add prototype properties (instance properties) to the subclass,
5874     // if supplied.
5875     if (protoProps) {
5876       ML._.extend(child.prototype, protoProps);
5877     }
5878 
5879     // Add static properties to the constructor function, if supplied.
5880     if (staticProps) {
5881       ML._.extend(child, staticProps);
5882     }
5883 
5884     // Correctly set child's `prototype.constructor`.
5885     child.prototype.constructor = child;
5886 
5887     // Set a convenience property in case the parent's prototype is
5888     // needed later.
5889     child.__super__ = parent.prototype;
5890 
5891     return child;
5892   };

5988   ML._getMLPath = function (path) {
5989     if (!ML.applicationId) {
5990       throw "You need to call ML.initialize before using ML.";
5991     }
5992     if (!path) {
5993       path = "";
5994     }
5995     if (!ML._.isString(path)) {
5996       throw "Tried to get a localStorage path that wasn't a String.";

6004   /**
6005    * Returns the unique string for this app on this machine.
6006    * Gets reset when localStorage is cleared.

6008   ML._installationId = null;
6009   ML._getInstallationId = function () {
6010     // See if it's cached in RAM.
6011     if (ML._installationId) {
6012       return ML._installationId;
6013     }
6014 
6015     // Try to get it from localStorage.
6016     var path = ML._getMLPath("installationId");

6018 
6019     if (!ML._installationId || ML._installationId === "") {
6020       // It wasn't in localStorage, so create a new one.
6021       var hexOctet = function () {
6022         return Math.floor((1 + Math.random()) * 0x10000).toString(16).substring(1);
6023       };
6024       ML._installationId = (
6025       hexOctet() + hexOctet() + "-" +
6026       hexOctet() + "-" +
6027       hexOctet() + "-" +
6028       hexOctet() + "-" +
6029       hexOctet() + hexOctet() + hexOctet());
6030       ML.localStorage.setItem(path, ML._installationId);

6036   ML._parseDate = function (iso8601) {
6037     var regexp = new RegExp(
6038       "^([0-9]{1,4})-([0-9]{1,2})-([0-9]{1,2})" + "T" +
6039       "([0-9]{1,2}):([0-9]{1,2}):([0-9]{1,2})" +
6040       "(.([0-9]+))?" + "Z$");
6041     var match = regexp.exec(iso8601);
6042     if (!match) {
6043       return null;
6044     }
6045 
6046     var year = match[1] || 0;
6047     var month = (match[2] || 1) - 1;
6048     var day = match[3] || 0;
6049     var hour = match[4] || 0;
6050     var minute = match[5] || 0;
6051     var second = match[6] || 0;
6052     var milli = match[8] || 0;
6053 
6054     return new Date(Date.UTC(year, month, day, hour, minute, second, milli));
6055   };

6057   ML._ajaxIE8 = function (method, url, data) {

6062       try {
6063         response = JSON.parse(xdr.responseText);
6064       } catch (e) {
6065         promise.reject(e);
6066       }
6067       if (response) {
6068         promise.resolve(response);
6069       }
6070     };
6071     xdr.onerror = xdr.ontimeout = function () {
6072       // Let's fake a real error message.

6074         responseText: JSON.stringify({
6075           code: ML.Error.X_DOMAIN_REQUEST,
6076           error: "IE's XDomainRequest does not supply error info."
6077         })
6078       };

6080     };
6081     xdr.onprogress = function () {
6082     };
6083     xdr.open(method, url);
6084     xdr.send(data);
6085     return promise;
6086   };

6092         // We're in IE 10+.
6093         return false;

6100   ML._ajax = function (method, url, data, success, error, headers) {
6101     var options = {
6102       success: success,
6103       error: error
6104     };
6105 
6106     if (ML._useXDomainRequest()) {
6107       return ML._ajaxIE8(method, url, data)._thenRunCallbacks(options);
6108     }
6109 
6110     var promise = new ML.Promise();
6111     var handled = false;
6112 
6113     var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
6114     xhr.onreadystatechange = function () {
6115       if (xhr.readyState === 4) {
6116         if (handled) {
6117           return;
6118         }
6119         handled = true;
6120 
6121         if (xhr.status >= 200 && xhr.status < 300) {
6122           var response;
6123           try {
6124             response = JSON.parse(xhr.responseText);
6125           } catch (e) {
6126             //对于一些请求(如delete files)，服务器不返回response，只能通过xhr.status判断请求结果
6127             promise.resolve(xhr.status);
6128           }
6129           if(xhr.status !== 204){ //204是文件删除接口的状态返回码
6130             if (response && !response.errorCode) {
6131               promise.resolve(response, xhr.status, xhr);
6132             }else{
6133               promise.reject(xhr);
6134             }
6135           }
6136 
6137         } else {
6138           promise.reject(xhr);
6139         }
6140       }
6141     };
6142     xhr.open(method, url, true);
6143     if(!url.match('analytics/at') && !url.match('track/event')){
6144       xhr.setRequestHeader("X-ML-AppId", ML.applicationId);
6145       xhr.setRequestHeader("X-ML-APIKey", ML.applicationKey);
6146     }
6147     
6148     for (var key in headers) {
6149       xhr.setRequestHeader(key, headers[key]);
6150     }
6151 
6152     //xhr.setRequestHeader("X-LAS-Fid", "zcf-7dd01734-8272-40de-89e7-dbb199f04bf9.txt");
6153 
6154     if (ML._isNode) {
6155       // Add a special user agent just for request from node.js.
6156       xhr.setRequestHeader("User-Agent",
6157         "ML/" + ML.VERSION +
6158         " (NodeJS " + process.versions.node + ")");
6159     }
6160     xhr.send(data);
6161     return promise._thenRunCallbacks(options);
6162   };

6171   /**
6172    * route is classes, users, login, etc.
6173    * objectId is null if there is no associated objectId.
6174    * method is the http method for the REST API.
6175    * dataObject is the payload as an object, or null if there is none.
6176    * headers is extra http headers.
6177    * @ignore
6178    */
6179   ML._request = function (route, className, objectId, method, dataObject, headers) {
6180     if (!ML.applicationId) {

6182     }

6262       }

6271     return ML._ajax(method, url, data, null, null, headers).then(null, function (response) {
6272       // Transform the error into an instance of ML.Error by trying to parse
6273       // the error string as JSON.
6274       var error;
6275       if (response && response.responseText) {

6277           var errorJSON = JSON.parse(response.responseText);
6278           if (errorJSON) {

6283         }

6286       // By explicitly returning a rejected Promise, this will work with
6287       // either jQuery or Promises/A semantics.

6292   // Helper function to get a value from a Backbone object as a property
6293   // or as a function.
6294   ML._getValue = function (object, prop) {
6295     if (!(object && object[prop])) {
6296       return null;
6297     }
6298     return ML._.isFunction(object[prop]) ? object[prop]() : object[prop];

6301   /**
6302    * Converts a value in a ML Object into the appropriate representation.
6303    * This is the JS equivalent of Java's ML.maybeReferenceAndEncode(Object)
6304    * if seenObjects is falsey. Otherwise any ML.Objects not in
6305    * seenObjects will be fully embedded rather than encoded
6306    * as a pointer.  This array will be used to prevent going into an infinite
6307    * loop because we have circular references.  If <seenObjects>
6308    * is set, then none of the ML Objects that are serialized can be dirty.
6309    */
6310   ML._encode = function (value, seenObjects, disallowObjects) {
6311     var _ = ML._;
6312     if (value instanceof ML.Object) {
6313       if (disallowObjects) {
6314         throw "ML.Objects not allowed here";
6315       }
6316       if (!seenObjects || _.include(seenObjects, value) || !value._hasData) {
6317         return value._toPointer();
6318       }
6319       if (!value.dirty()) {
6320         seenObjects = seenObjects.concat(value);
6321         return ML._encode(value._toFullJSON(seenObjects),
6322           seenObjects,
6323           disallowObjects);
6324       }
6325       throw "Tried to save an object with a pointer to a new, unsaved object.";
6326     }
6327     if (_.isDate(value)) {
6328       return {"__type": "Date", "iso": value.toJSON()};
6329     }
6330     if (value instanceof ML.GeoPoint) {
6331       return value.toJSON();
6332     }
6333     if (_.isArray(value)) {
6334       return _.map(value, function (x) {
6335         return ML._encode(x, seenObjects, disallowObjects);
6336       });
6337     }
6338     if (_.isRegExp(value)) {
6339       return value.source;
6340     }
6341     if (value instanceof ML.Relation) {
6342       return value.toJSON();
6343     }
6344     if (value instanceof ML.Op) {
6345       return value.toJSON();
6346     }
6347     if (value instanceof ML.File) {
6348       if (!value.url() && !value.id) {
6349         throw "Tried to save an object containing an unsaved file.";
6350       }
6351       return {
6352         __type: "File",
6353         id: value.id,
6354         name: value.name(),
6355         url: value.url()
6356       };
6357     }
6358     if (_.isObject(value)) {
6359       var output = {};
6360       ML._objectEach(value, function (v, k) {
6361         output[k] = ML._encode(v, seenObjects, disallowObjects);
6362       });
6363       return output;
6364     }
6365     return value;
6366   };
6367 
6368   /**
6369    * The inverse function of ML._encode.
6370    * TODO: make decode not mutate value.
6371    */
6372   ML._decode = function (key, value) {
6373     var _ = ML._;
6374     if (!_.isObject(value)) {
6375       return value;
6376     }
6377     if (_.isArray(value)) {
6378       ML._arrayEach(value, function (v, k) {
6379         value[k] = ML._decode(k, v);
6380       });
6381       return value;
6382     }
6383     if (value instanceof ML.Object) {
6384       return value;
6385     }
6386     if (value instanceof ML.File) {
6387       return value;
6388     }
6389     if (value instanceof ML.Op) {
6390       return value;
6391     }
6392     if (value.__op) {
6393       return ML.Op._decode(value);
6394     }
6395     if (value.__type === "Pointer") {
6396       var className = value.className;
6397       var pointer = ML.Object._create(className);
6398       if (value.createdAt) {
6399         delete value.__type;
6400         delete value.className;
6401         pointer._finishFetch(value, true);
6402       } else {
6403         pointer._finishFetch({objectId: value.objectId}, false);
6404       }
6405       return pointer;
6406     }
6407     if (value.__type === "Object") {
6408       // It's an Object included in a query result.
6409       var className = value.className;
6410       delete value.__type;
6411       delete value.className;
6412       var object = ML.Object._create(className);
6413       object._finishFetch(value, true);
6414       return object;
6415     }
6416     if (value.__type === "Date") {
6417       return ML._parseDate(value.iso);
6418     }
6419     if (value.__type === "GeoPoint") {
6420       return new ML.GeoPoint({
6421         latitude: value.latitude,
6422         longitude: value.longitude
6423       });
6424     }
6425     if (value.__type === "Relation") {
6426       var relation = new ML.Relation(null, key);
6427       relation.targetClassName = value.className;
6428       return relation;
6429     }
6430     if (value.__type === "File") {
6431       var file = new ML.File(value.name);
6432       file._metaData = value.metaData || {};
6433       file._url = value.url;
6434       file.id = value.objectId;
6435       return file;
6436     }
6437     ML._objectEach(value, function (v, k) {
6438       value[k] = ML._decode(k, v);
6439     });
6440     return value;
6441   };
6442 
6443   ML._arrayEach = ML._.each;
6444 
6445   /**
6446    * Does a deep traversal of every item in object, calling func on every one.
6447    * @param {Object} object The object or array to traverse deeply.
6448    * @param {Function} func The function to call for every item. It will
6449    *     be passed the item as an argument. If it returns a truthy value, that
6450    *     value will replace the item in its parent container.
6451    * @returns {} the result of calling func on the top-level object itself.
6452    */
6453   ML._traverse = function (object, func, seen) {
6454     if (object instanceof ML.Object) {
6455       seen = seen || [];
6456       if (ML._.indexOf(seen, object) >= 0) {
6457         // We've already visited this object in this call.
6458         return;
6459       }
6460       seen.push(object);
6461       ML._traverse(object.attributes, func, seen);
6462       return func(object);
6463     }
6464     if (object instanceof ML.Relation || object instanceof ML.File) {
6465       // Nothing needs to be done, but we don't want to recurse into the
6466       // object's parent infinitely, so we catch this case.
6467       return func(object);
6468     }
6469     if (ML._.isArray(object)) {
6470       ML._.each(object, function (child, index) {
6471         var newChild = ML._traverse(child, func, seen);
6472         if (newChild) {
6473           object[index] = newChild;
6474         }
6475       });
6476       return func(object);
6477     }
6478     if (ML._.isObject(object)) {
6479       ML._each(object, function (child, key) {
6480         var newChild = ML._traverse(child, func, seen);
6481         if (newChild) {
6482           object[key] = newChild;
6483         }
6484       });
6485       return func(object);
6486     }
6487     return func(object);
6488   };
6489 
6490   /**
6491    * This is like _.each, except:
6492    * * it doesn't work for so-called array-like objects,
6493    * * it does work for dictionaries with a "length" attribute.
6494    */
6495   ML._objectEach = ML._each = function (obj, callback) {
6496     var _ = ML._;
6497     if (_.isObject(obj)) {
6498       _.each(_.keys(obj), function (key) {
6499         callback(obj[key], key);
6500       });
6501     } else {
6502       _.each(obj, callback);
6503     }
6504   };

6507   ML._isNullOrUndefined = function (x) {
6508     return ML._.isNull(x) || ML._.isUndefined(x);
6509   };

6627      *

6629      *       'mousedown .title':  'edit',

6635      * Uses event delegation for efficiency.
6636      * Omitting the selector binds the event to `this.el`.
6637      * This only works for delegate-able events: not `focus`, `blur`, and

6640     delegateEvents: function(events) {
6641       events = events || ML._getValue(this, 'events');
6642       if (!events) {

6970     var clockseq = options.clockseq != null ? options.clockseq : _clockseq;
6971 
6972     // UUID timestamps are 100 nano-second units since the Gregorian epoch,
6973     // (1582-10-15 00:00).  JSNumbers aren't precise enough for this, so
6974     // time is handled internally as 'msecs' (integer milliseconds) and 'nsecs'
6975     // (100-nanoseconds offset from msecs) since unix epoch, 1970-01-01 00:00.
6976     var msecs = options.msecs != null ? options.msecs : new Date().getTime();

6979     // cycle to simulate higher resolution clock
6980     var nsecs = options.nsecs != null ? options.nsecs : _lastNSecs + 1;

6983     var dt = (msecs - _lastMSecs) + (nsecs - _lastNSecs)/10000;

6985     // Per 4.2.1.2, Bump clockseq on clock regression

6997     if (nsecs >= 10000) {

7494   // Determine if at least one element in the object matches a truth test.
7495   // Aliased as `any`.
7496   _.some = _.any = function(obj, predicate, context) {
7497     predicate = cb(predicate, context);
7498     var keys = !isArrayLike(obj) && _.keys(obj),
7499         length = (keys || obj).length;
7500     for (var index = 0; index < length; index++) {
7501       var currentKey = keys ? keys[index] : index;
7502       if (predicate(obj[currentKey], currentKey, obj)) return true;
7503     }
7504     return false;
7505   };
7506 
7507   // Determine if the array or object contains a given item (using `===`).
7508   // Aliased as `includes` and `include`.
7509   _.contains = _.includes = _.include = function(obj, item, fromIndex, guard) {
7510     if (!isArrayLike(obj)) obj = _.values(obj);
7511     if (typeof fromIndex != 'number' || guard) fromIndex = 0;
7512     return _.indexOf(obj, item, fromIndex) >= 0;
7513   };
7514 
7515   // Invoke a method (with arguments) on every item in a collection.
7516   _.invoke = function(obj, method) {
7517     var args = slice.call(arguments, 2);
7518     var isFunc = _.isFunction(method);
7519     return _.map(obj, function(value) {
7520       var func = isFunc ? method : value[method];
7521       return func == null ? func : func.apply(value, args);
7522     });
7523   };

7525   // Convenience version of a common use case of `map`: fetching a property.
7526   _.pluck = function(obj, key) {
7527     return _.map(obj, _.property(key));
7528   };

7530   // Convenience version of a common use case of `filter`: selecting only objects
7531   // containing specific `key:value` pairs.
7532   _.where = function(obj, attrs) {
7533     return _.filter(obj, _.matcher(attrs));
7534   };
7535 
7536   // Convenience version of a common use case of `find`: getting the first object
7537   // containing specific `key:value` pairs.
7538   _.findWhere = function(obj, attrs) {
7539     return _.find(obj, _.matcher(attrs));
7540   };

7542   // Return the maximum element (or element-based computation).
7543   _.max = function(obj, iteratee, context) {
7544     var result = -Infinity, lastComputed = -Infinity,
7545         value, computed;
7546     if (iteratee == null && obj != null) {
7547       obj = isArrayLike(obj) ? obj : _.values(obj);
7548       for (var i = 0, length = obj.length; i < length; i++) {
7549         value = obj[i];
7550         if (value > result) {
7551           result = value;
7552         }
7553       }
7554     } else {
7555       iteratee = cb(iteratee, context);
7556       _.each(obj, function(value, index, list) {
7557         computed = iteratee(value, index, list);
7558         if (computed > lastComputed || computed === -Infinity && result === -Infinity) {
7559           result = value;
7560           lastComputed = computed;
7561         }
7562       });
7563     }
7564     return result;
7565   };
7566 
7567   // Return the minimum element (or element-based computation).
7568   _.min = function(obj, iteratee, context) {
7569     var result = Infinity, lastComputed = Infinity,
7570         value, computed;
7571     if (iteratee == null && obj != null) {
7572       obj = isArrayLike(obj) ? obj : _.values(obj);
7573       for (var i = 0, length = obj.length; i < length; i++) {
7574         value = obj[i];
7575         if (value < result) {
7576           result = value;
7577         }
7578       }
7579     } else {
7580       iteratee = cb(iteratee, context);
7581       _.each(obj, function(value, index, list) {
7582         computed = iteratee(value, index, list);
7583         if (computed < lastComputed || computed === Infinity && result === Infinity) {
7584           result = value;
7585           lastComputed = computed;
7586         }
7587       });
7588     }
7589     return result;
7590   };

7592   // Shuffle a collection, using the modern version of the
7593   // [Fisher-Yates shuffle](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisher–Yates_shuffle).
7594   _.shuffle = function(obj) {
7595     var set = isArrayLike(obj) ? obj : _.values(obj);
7596     var length = set.length;
7597     var shuffled = Array(length);
7598     for (var index = 0, rand; index < length; index++) {
7599       rand = _.random(0, index);
7600       if (rand !== index) shuffled[index] = shuffled[rand];
7601       shuffled[rand] = set[index];
7602     }
7603     return shuffled;
7604   };
7605 
7606   // Sample **n** random values from a collection.
7607   // If **n** is not specified, returns a single random element.
7608   // The internal `guard` argument allows it to work with `map`.
7609   _.sample = function(obj, n, guard) {
7610     if (n == null || guard) {
7611       if (!isArrayLike(obj)) obj = _.values(obj);
7612       return obj[_.random(obj.length - 1)];
7613     }
7614     return _.shuffle(obj).slice(0, Math.max(0, n));
7615   };

7617   // Sort the object's values by a criterion produced by an iteratee.
7618   _.sortBy = function(obj, iteratee, context) {
7619     iteratee = cb(iteratee, context);
7620     return _.pluck(_.map(obj, function(value, index, list) {
7621       return {
7622         value: value,
7623         index: index,
7624         criteria: iteratee(value, index, list)
7625       };
7626     }).sort(function(left, right) {
7627       var a = left.criteria;
7628       var b = right.criteria;
7629       if (a !== b) {
7630         if (a > b || a === void 0) return 1;
7631         if (a < b || b === void 0) return -1;
7632       }
7633       return left.index - right.index;
7634     }), 'value');
7635   };

7637   // An internal function used for aggregate "group by" operations.
7638   var group = function(behavior) {
7639     return function(obj, iteratee, context) {
7640       var result = {};
7641       iteratee = cb(iteratee, context);
7642       _.each(obj, function(value, index) {
7643         var key = iteratee(value, index, obj);
7644         behavior(result, value, key);
7645       });
7646       return result;
7647     };
7648   };

7650   // Groups the object's values by a criterion. Pass either a string attribute
7651   // to group by, or a function that returns the criterion.
7652   _.groupBy = group(function(result, value, key) {
7653     if (_.has(result, key)) result[key].push(value); else result[key] = [value];
7654   });
7655 
7656   // Indexes the object's values by a criterion, similar to `groupBy`, but for
7657   // when you know that your index values will be unique.
7658   _.indexBy = group(function(result, value, key) {
7659     result[key] = value;
7660   });
7661 
7662   // Counts instances of an object that group by a certain criterion. Pass
7663   // either a string attribute to count by, or a function that returns the
7664   // criterion.
7665   _.countBy = group(function(result, value, key) {
7666     if (_.has(result, key)) result[key]++; else result[key] = 1;
7667   });

7669   // Safely create a real, live array from anything iterable.
7670   _.toArray = function(obj) {
7671     if (!obj) return [];
7672     if (_.isArray(obj)) return slice.call(obj);
7673     if (isArrayLike(obj)) return _.map(obj, _.identity);
7674     return _.values(obj);
7675   };

7677   // Return the number of elements in an object.
7678   _.size = function(obj) {
7679     if (obj == null) return 0;
7680     return isArrayLike(obj) ? obj.length : _.keys(obj).length;
7681   };

7683   // Split a collection into two arrays: one whose elements all satisfy the given
7684   // predicate, and one whose elements all do not satisfy the predicate.
7685   _.partition = function(obj, predicate, context) {
7686     predicate = cb(predicate, context);
7687     var pass = [], fail = [];
7688     _.each(obj, function(value, key, obj) {
7689       (predicate(value, key, obj) ? pass : fail).push(value);
7690     });
7691     return [pass, fail];
7692   };

7697   // Get the first element of an array. Passing **n** will return the first N
7698   // values in the array. Aliased as `head` and `take`. The **guard** check
7699   // allows it to work with `_.map`.
7700   _.first = _.head = _.take = function(array, n, guard) {
7701     if (array == null) return void 0;
7702     if (n == null || guard) return array[0];
7703     return _.initial(array, array.length - n);
7704   };
7705 
7706   // Returns everything but the last entry of the array. Especially useful on
7707   // the arguments object. Passing **n** will return all the values in
7708   // the array, excluding the last N.
7709   _.initial = function(array, n, guard) {
7710     return slice.call(array, 0, Math.max(0, array.length - (n == null || guard ? 1 : n)));
7711   };
7712 
7713   // Get the last element of an array. Passing **n** will return the last N
7714   // values in the array.
7715   _.last = function(array, n, guard) {
7716     if (array == null) return void 0;
7717     if (n == null || guard) return array[array.length - 1];
7718     return _.rest(array, Math.max(0, array.length - n));
7719   };
7720 
7721   // Returns everything but the first entry of the array. Aliased as `tail` and `drop`.
7722   // Especially useful on the arguments object. Passing an **n** will return
7723   // the rest N values in the array.
7724   _.rest = _.tail = _.drop = function(array, n, guard) {
7725     return slice.call(array, n == null || guard ? 1 : n);
7726   };

7728   // Trim out all falsy values from an array.
7729   _.compact = function(array) {
7730     return _.filter(array, _.identity);
7731   };

7733   // Internal implementation of a recursive `flatten` function.
7734   var flatten = function(input, shallow, strict, startIndex) {
7735     var output = [], idx = 0;
7736     for (var i = startIndex || 0, length = getLength(input); i < length; i++) {
7737       var value = input[i];
7738       if (isArrayLike(value) && (_.isArray(value) || _.isArguments(value))) {
7739         //flatten current level of array or arguments object
7740         if (!shallow) value = flatten(value, shallow, strict);
7741         var j = 0, len = value.length;
7742         output.length += len;
7743         while (j < len) {
7744           output[idx++] = value[j++];
7745         }
7746       } else if (!strict) {
7747         output[idx++] = value;
7748       }
7749     }
7750     return output;
7751   };
7752 
7753   // Flatten out an array, either recursively (by default), or just one level.
7754   _.flatten = function(array, shallow) {
7755     return flatten(array, shallow, false);
7756   };
7757 
7758   // Return a version of the array that does not contain the specified value(s).
7759   _.without = function(array) {
7760     return _.difference(array, slice.call(arguments, 1));
7761   };

7763   // Produce a duplicate-free version of the array. If the array has already
7764   // been sorted, you have the option of using a faster algorithm.
7765   // Aliased as `unique`.
7766   _.uniq = _.unique = function(array, isSorted, iteratee, context) {
7767     if (!_.isBoolean(isSorted)) {
7768       context = iteratee;
7769       iteratee = isSorted;
7770       isSorted = false;
7771     }
7772     if (iteratee != null) iteratee = cb(iteratee, context);
7773     var result = [];
7774     var seen = [];
7775     for (var i = 0, length = getLength(array); i < length; i++) {
7776       var value = array[i],
7777           computed = iteratee ? iteratee(value, i, array) : value;
7778       if (isSorted) {
7779         if (!i || seen !== computed) result.push(value);
7780         seen = computed;
7781       } else if (iteratee) {
7782         if (!_.contains(seen, computed)) {
7783           seen.push(computed);
7784           result.push(value);
7785         }
7786       } else if (!_.contains(result, value)) {
7787         result.push(value);
7788       }
7789     }
7790     return result;
7791   };
7792 
7793   // Produce an array that contains the union: each distinct element from all of
7794   // the passed-in arrays.
7795   _.union = function() {
7796     return _.uniq(flatten(arguments, true, true));
7797   };
7798 
7799   // Produce an array that contains every item shared between all the
7800   // passed-in arrays.
7801   _.intersection = function(array) {
7802     var result = [];
7803     var argsLength = arguments.length;
7804     for (var i = 0, length = getLength(array); i < length; i++) {
7805       var item = array[i];
7806       if (_.contains(result, item)) continue;
7807       for (var j = 1; j < argsLength; j++) {
7808         if (!_.contains(arguments[j], item)) break;
7809       }
7810       if (j === argsLength) result.push(item);
7811     }
7812     return result;
7813   };
7814 
7815   // Take the difference between one array and a number of other arrays.
7816   // Only the elements present in just the first array will remain.
7817   _.difference = function(array) {
7818     var rest = flatten(arguments, true, true, 1);
7819     return _.filter(array, function(value){
7820       return !_.contains(rest, value);
7821     });
7822   };

7824   // Zip together multiple lists into a single array -- elements that share
7825   // an index go together.
7826   _.zip = function() {
7827     return _.unzip(arguments);
7828   };

7830   // Complement of _.zip. Unzip accepts an array of arrays and groups
7831   // each array's elements on shared indices
7832   _.unzip = function(array) {
7833     var length = array && _.max(array, getLength).length || 0;
7834     var result = Array(length);
7835 
7836     for (var index = 0; index < length; index++) {
7837       result[index] = _.pluck(array, index);
7838     }
7839     return result;
7840   };

7842   // Converts lists into objects. Pass either a single array of `[key, value]`
7843   // pairs, or two parallel arrays of the same length -- one of keys, and one of
7844   // the corresponding values.
7845   _.object = function(list, values) {
7846     var result = {};
7847     for (var i = 0, length = getLength(list); i < length; i++) {
7848       if (values) {
7849         result[list[i]] = values[i];
7850       } else {
7851         result[list[i][0]] = list[i][1];
7852       }
7853     }
7854     return result;
7855   };

7857   // Generator function to create the findIndex and findLastIndex functions
7858   function createPredicateIndexFinder(dir) {
7859     return function(array, predicate, context) {
7860       predicate = cb(predicate, context);
7861       var length = getLength(array);
7862       var index = dir > 0 ? 0 : length - 1;
7863       for (; index >= 0 && index < length; index += dir) {
7864         if (predicate(array[index], index, array)) return index;
7865       }
7866       return -1;
7867     };
7868   }
7869 
7870   // Returns the first index on an array-like that passes a predicate test
7871   _.findIndex = createPredicateIndexFinder(1);
7872   _.findLastIndex = createPredicateIndexFinder(-1);
7873 
7874   // Use a comparator function to figure out the smallest index at which
7875   // an object should be inserted so as to maintain order. Uses binary search.
7876   _.sortedIndex = function(array, obj, iteratee, context) {
7877     iteratee = cb(iteratee, context, 1);
7878     var value = iteratee(obj);
7879     var low = 0, high = getLength(array);
7880     while (low < high) {
7881       var mid = Math.floor((low + high) / 2);
7882       if (iteratee(array[mid]) < value) low = mid + 1; else high = mid;
7883     }
7884     return low;
7885   };
7886 
7887   // Generator function to create the indexOf and lastIndexOf functions
7888   function createIndexFinder(dir, predicateFind, sortedIndex) {
7889     return function(array, item, idx) {
7890       var i = 0, length = getLength(array);
7891       if (typeof idx == 'number') {
7892         if (dir > 0) {
7893             i = idx >= 0 ? idx : Math.max(idx + length, i);
7894         } else {
7895             length = idx >= 0 ? Math.min(idx + 1, length) : idx + length + 1;
7896         }
7897       } else if (sortedIndex && idx && length) {
7898         idx = sortedIndex(array, item);
7899         return array[idx] === item ? idx : -1;
7900       }
7901       if (item !== item) {
7902         idx = predicateFind(slice.call(array, i, length), _.isNaN);
7903         return idx >= 0 ? idx + i : -1;
7904       }
7905       for (idx = dir > 0 ? i : length - 1; idx >= 0 && idx < length; idx += dir) {
7906         if (array[idx] === item) return idx;
7907       }
7908       return -1;
7909     };
7910   }

7912   // Return the position of the first occurrence of an item in an array,
7913   // or -1 if the item is not included in the array.
7914   // If the array is large and already in sort order, pass `true`
7915   // for **isSorted** to use binary search.
7916   _.indexOf = createIndexFinder(1, _.findIndex, _.sortedIndex);
7917   _.lastIndexOf = createIndexFinder(-1, _.findLastIndex);
7918 
7919   // Generate an integer Array containing an arithmetic progression. A port of
7920   // the native Python `range()` function. See
7921   // [the Python documentation](http://docs.python.org/library/functions.html#range).
7922   _.range = function(start, stop, step) {
7923     if (stop == null) {
7924       stop = start || 0;
7925       start = 0;
7926     }
7927     step = step || 1;
7928 
7929     var length = Math.max(Math.ceil((stop - start) / step), 0);
7930     var range = Array(length);
7931 
7932     for (var idx = 0; idx < length; idx++, start += step) {
7933       range[idx] = start;
7934     }
7935 
7936     return range;
7937   };
